\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 23. G. palustre} L.,{\i  Cent. Pl.}{\b  2}: 25 (1756). Perennial, with thin, fibrous roots, arising from a short rhizome. Stems 20-60 cm, erect or spreading, with patent or somewhat deflexed hairs. Leaves 5-10 cm wide, divided for 80-85 % of the radius into 5-7 obovate-cuneate, incise-dentate lobes. Inflorescence diffuse, few-flowered; fruiting pedicels deflexed, 2-4 times as long as the sepals, densely pubescent. Sepals 10-13 mm, with arista usually c. 2 mm, glabrous except for short, appressed hairs on the veins; petals 12-18 mm, entire or very slightly emarginate, purple or lilac, hairy on inner surface at extreme base. Mericarps hairy, without ridges. 2n = 28.{\i  Throughout a large part of Europe, but absent from the islands, the Mediterranean region and much of the north.} Au Be Bu Cz Da Fe Ga Ge He ?Hs Hu It Ju Po Rm Rs (N, B, C, W, E) Su.
